#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""exec-hook-bridge — bridge a cross-arch hook invocation to the host
via the host-bash MCP server.

WHY THIS EXISTS

When `exec-hook` (the magic-byte sniffing wrapper at
container/hooks-shim/exec-hook) detects a Mach-O / wrong-arch binary,
its default safe behaviour is to silently no-op so the in-container
session doesn't spam "Exec format error" on every hook firing. That
keeps the session usable but means real telemetry / corp hooks never
actually run — q-0202 / PR #164 deferred the bridge work as too-big
for that PR. This helper is the deferred fix: instead of silently
no-op'ing, exec-hook can ask THIS script to marshal the call across
host-bash MCP. The host runs the real hook binary with the same env
+ stdin payload Claude Code passed, and the result returns to the
container so the in-container claude sees the same outcome as if
the hook ran locally.

WIRING

Triggered from exec-hook when:
  1. The target binary is Mach-O / unknown format (would have been
     no-op'd), AND
  2. CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE=1 in the environment (default OFF —
     opt-in until operators can verify the host-side allow-list
     covers their hook binary).

exec-hook invokes:
  exec-hook-bridge <target> [args...]

with the original hook stdin payload streamed in on stdin. Env vars
exported by Claude Code at hook time (CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR,
CLAUDE_SESSION_ID, etc.) are forwarded to the host call so the host
binary sees the same context.

On bridge success, this helper exits with the host binary's exit
code. On bridge failure (host-bash unreachable, JSON-RPC error,
allow-list rejection), this helper exits 0 and emits a single stderr
line so the operator can see WHY the bridge fell back. The
fall-back-to-no-op behaviour is the safety floor: a misconfigured
bridge MUST NOT bring the session down.

PROTOCOL

host-bash MCP runs at host.docker.internal:8766/mcp by default
(overridable via CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_URL). It speaks the standard
MCP HTTP transport — JSON-RPC 2.0 over POST. The single tool we
invoke is `run_command`, exposed by cli-mcp-server, with arguments:
  - command: the binary to exec on the host (absolute path or
    basename — cli-mcp-server resolves bare names against $PATH and
    enforces its ALLOWED_COMMANDS allow-list)
  - args: a list of string args (forwarded verbatim from our argv)

STREAMABLE-HTTP SESSION HANDSHAKE

mcp-proxy 0.11+ uses the MCP streamable-HTTP transport with
`stateless=False` by default. A bare POST of `tools/call` against a
fresh connection returns HTTP 400 ("Bad Request: Missing session ID")
— the client MUST first POST a JSON-RPC `initialize` request,
capture the server-issued `mcp-session-id` from the response headers,
and include that header on every subsequent request.

The bridge therefore makes 2 or 3 sequential POSTs:

  1. POST <url>  initialize request -> response carries the
                 `mcp-session-id` header. The body is the standard
                 initialize ack (serverInfo + capabilities).
  2. POST <url>  `notifications/initialized` (notification — no `id`,
                 no response body beyond HTTP 202). Sent with the
                 mcp-session-id header. Some MCP implementations
                 enforce this before tools/* calls; we send it for
                 protocol-correctness even when the current
                 mcp-proxy + SDK don't enforce it.
  3. POST <url>  `tools/call` with the mcp-session-id header. The
                 response is parsed for the cli-mcp-server
                 `run_command` text body shape.

The whole handshake stays within `CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT`
(applied per-request) — typical handshake completes in <100ms on a
warm mcp-proxy. Failures at any step fall back to silent no-op via
the same path as a transport-level failure.

cli-mcp-server's `run_command` does NOT support stdin; we work around
this by writing the stdin payload to a host-visible tempfile (via a
secondary `run_command` to `tee`), then redirecting that file into
the host binary on a second call. Operators who don't bind-mount a
shared tempdir between container and host get a degraded-mode warning
+ silent fall-through (the bridge can't deliver stdin without a
shared writable path).

DEGRADED MODE — STDIN-LESS HOOKS

When stdin is empty (the hook doesn't read it) we skip the
shared-tempdir handshake entirely and call the host binary directly.
SessionStart / SessionEnd hooks per Claude Code's docs receive a JSON
event payload on stdin, BUT some operator hooks ignore it and read
their context from env vars + their own configuration. For those, the
no-stdin fast path is the production case.

EXIT CODES

  <N>   the host binary's exit code, propagated verbatim
  0     bridge fell back (host-bash unreachable, allow-list reject,
        URL unset, etc.) — this matches the original silent-no-op
        contract so the session keeps running
  2     argv parse error (bad invocation from exec-hook itself)

ENVIRONMENT

  CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE     — must be `1` for the bridge to fire.
                                Other values (including unset) =
                                fall-back behaviour. Default OFF.
  CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_URL — full MCP endpoint URL. Default
                                http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp .
                                Operators with a custom port / path
                                set this in compose.yml's `environment`.
  CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER
                              — bearer token sent as
                                `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on every
                                request, when the host launcher is
                                running behind mcp-proxy-auth-shim. Must
                                match MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER on the host
                                launcher side. Empty / unset = no
                                Authorization header sent (works against
                                a launcher that doesn't have a bearer
                                configured; gets 401-rejected by a
                                launcher that does). Default unset.
  CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT
                              — seconds to wait for the JSON-RPC call.
                                Default 30. Hooks that take longer
                                than this are killed by the bridge.
  CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_DEBUG
                              — if `1`, print every JSON-RPC request /
                                response payload to stderr. Default
                                OFF (production = silent on success).
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import json
import os
import sys
import urllib.error
import urllib.request

# Default endpoint matches the documented mcp-host-bash port (8766).
DEFAULT_BRIDGE_URL = "http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp"
DEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 30

# MCP streamable-HTTP transport constants. Pinned to a real protocol
# version (2025-06-18 is the version mcp-proxy 0.11.x ships against).
# If the server prefers a different version it negotiates down in the
# initialize response; we don't enforce a match here because the
# subsequent tools/call doesn't care which version was picked.
MCP_PROTOCOL_VERSION = "2025-06-18"
MCP_SESSION_ID_HEADER = "mcp-session-id"
MCP_CLIENT_INFO = {
    "name": "claude-watch/exec-hook-bridge",
    # Bumped when the bridge's wire shape changes in a way servers
    # might log or branch on. Independent of the claude-watch crate
    # version (this script ships in the image, not in cargo).
    "version": "1",
}


# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Helpers
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------


def emit(msg: str) -> None:
    """One-line stderr emit, prefixed so operators can grep for bridge
    activity in their session logs without filtering the rest of the
    container stderr."""
    print(f"[hook-bridge] {msg}", file=sys.stderr)


def emit_debug(msg: str) -> None:
    if os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_DEBUG") == "1":
        emit(msg)


def parse_argv(argv: list[str]) -> tuple[str, list[str]]:
    """Return (target_binary, args). Exits 2 on bad invocation."""
    if len(argv) < 2:
        emit("usage: exec-hook-bridge <target> [args...] (called with no target)")
        sys.exit(2)
    return (argv[1], argv[2:])


def collect_forwarded_env() -> dict[str, str]:
    """Pick up Claude-Code-injected env vars to forward to the host call.

    Claude Code exports a small set of well-known env vars to hook
    invocations (project dir, session id, hook event name, transcript
    path). We forward those plus anything the operator has whitelisted
    via CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_FORWARD_ENV (colon-separated list of
    extra var names — comma is reserved for cli-mcp-server's
    ALLOWED_COMMANDS so we use colon to match the rest of the
    container's bridge env conventions).

    Returns a dict the host binary will see as its environment additions
    via cli-mcp-server's per-call `env` arg (when supported) — today
    cli-mcp-server doesn't accept per-call env, so we fold the env
    forwards into a small `env KEY=VAL ... <bin>` shell prefix on the
    host side. That keeps the surface area narrow + auditable.
    """
    well_known = [
        "CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR",
        "CLAUDE_SESSION_ID",
        "CLAUDE_HOOK_EVENT",
        "CLAUDE_TRANSCRIPT_PATH",
    ]
    extra_raw = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_FORWARD_ENV", "")
    extras = [k for k in extra_raw.split(":") if k]
    forwarded: dict[str, str] = {}
    for k in well_known + extras:
        v = os.environ.get(k)
        if v is not None:
            forwarded[k] = v
    return forwarded


def bridge_url() -> str:
    return os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_URL", DEFAULT_BRIDGE_URL)


def bearer_header() -> dict[str, str]:
    """Return `{"Authorization": "Bearer <token>"}` if
    CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER is set, else empty dict.

    The shim on the host side (mcp-proxy-auth-shim) validates this
    header on every request when the launcher is configured with
    MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER. If the host launcher is running WITHOUT
    bearer auth (older deployments / loopback-only setups), the
    header is harmless — mcp-proxy ignores it. If the host launcher
    is running WITH bearer auth and we don't send the header, the
    shim 401's us and the bridge falls back to no-op (the standard
    misconfig safety net).
    """
    token = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER", "")
    if not token:
        return {}
    return {"Authorization": f"Bearer {token}"}


def bridge_timeout() -> float:
    raw = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT")
    if not raw:
        return float(DEFAULT_TIMEOUT)
    try:
        return float(raw)
    except ValueError:
        emit(f"invalid CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT={raw!r}, using default {DEFAULT_TIMEOUT}s")
        return float(DEFAULT_TIMEOUT)


# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# JSON-RPC client
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------


def jsonrpc_post(
    url: str,
    payload: dict,
    timeout: float,
    extra_headers: dict[str, str] | None = None,
) -> tuple[dict | None, dict[str, str], int]:
    """POST a JSON-RPC 2.0 payload, return (parsed_body, response_headers, status).

    `payload` may be a request (with `id`) or a notification (without `id`).
    For notifications the server typically returns HTTP 202 with no body;
    `parsed_body` is None in that case.

    `extra_headers` lets the caller inject the streamable-HTTP
    `mcp-session-id` header on follow-up calls.

    `response_headers` is a dict the caller can read for the
    server-issued `mcp-session-id` after the initialize call.

    Raises on transport error / non-2xx / unparseable JSON body. The
    caller decides whether to fall back to no-op based on the exception
    type.
    """
    body = json.dumps(payload).encode("utf-8")
    method = payload.get("method", "<unknown>")
    emit_debug(f"-> POST {url} method={method}")
    emit_debug(f"   payload={json.dumps(payload)[:512]}")
    headers = {
        "Content-Type": "application/json",
        "Accept": "application/json, text/event-stream",
    }
    if extra_headers:
        headers.update(extra_headers)
    req = urllib.request.Request(url, data=body, method="POST", headers=headers)
    with urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=timeout) as resp:
        raw = resp.read().decode("utf-8", errors="replace")
        emit_debug(f"<- {resp.status} {raw[:512]}")
        # Header keys are case-insensitive on the wire; normalize to
        # lowercase so the caller can `.get("mcp-session-id")` without
        # worrying about server casing (`Mcp-Session-Id` etc).
        resp_headers = {k.lower(): v for k, v in resp.headers.items()}
        if not raw.strip():
            # Notification ack (HTTP 202 with empty body) — no JSON to
            # parse. Return None body so the caller knows not to
            # interpret it as a response.
            return (None, resp_headers, resp.status)
        # mcp-proxy may reply as text/event-stream OR JSON. The MCP
        # streamable-HTTP transport allows either — for a one-shot
        # tools/call we accept both shapes.
        ct = resp.headers.get("Content-Type", "")
        if "text/event-stream" in ct:
            # SSE: parse the first `data: <json>` line.
            for line in raw.splitlines():
                if line.startswith("data:"):
                    return (
                        json.loads(line[len("data:"):].strip()),
                        resp_headers,
                        resp.status,
                    )
            raise ValueError(f"SSE response had no `data:` frame: {raw[:200]!r}")
        return (json.loads(raw), resp_headers, resp.status)


def initialize_session(url: str, timeout: float) -> str:
    """Run the MCP streamable-HTTP session handshake.

    POSTs `initialize`, captures the server-issued `mcp-session-id`,
    then POSTs `notifications/initialized` so a strict server transitions
    from "initializing" to "ready" before our tools/call.

    Returns the session id. Raises if the handshake fails (transport
    error, missing session-id header, JSON-RPC error envelope).
    """
    init_payload = {
        "jsonrpc": "2.0",
        "id": 1,
        "method": "initialize",
        "params": {
            "protocolVersion": MCP_PROTOCOL_VERSION,
            "capabilities": {},
            "clientInfo": MCP_CLIENT_INFO,
        },
    }
    auth_headers = bearer_header()
    body, headers, _status = jsonrpc_post(
        url, init_payload, timeout=timeout,
        extra_headers=auth_headers if auth_headers else None,
    )
    if body and "error" in body:
        # JSON-RPC error envelope on initialize — surface upwards.
        err = body["error"]
        msg = err.get("message", str(err)) if isinstance(err, dict) else str(err)
        raise ValueError(f"initialize returned JSON-RPC error: {msg}")
    session_id = headers.get(MCP_SESSION_ID_HEADER)
    if not session_id:
        # Streamable-HTTP server that didn't issue a session id is
        # either misconfigured or `stateless=True` — the latter is
        # valid + needs no session header on follow-ups. We treat
        # missing-header as "stateless mode" so the bridge still
        # works against a stateless proxy. Caller's tools/call will
        # be sent without the header in that case.
        emit_debug("initialize: no mcp-session-id returned; assuming stateless mode")
        return ""

    # Fire the notifications/initialized acknowledgment. Strict MCP
    # servers stay in "initializing" until they see this; lax ones
    # (current mcp-proxy / python-sdk) don't enforce it but accept it
    # silently. Sent as a JSON-RPC notification (no `id` -> no
    # response envelope expected).
    initialized_payload = {
        "jsonrpc": "2.0",
        "method": "notifications/initialized",
        "params": {},
    }
    try:
        notif_headers = {MCP_SESSION_ID_HEADER: session_id}
        notif_headers.update(bearer_header())
        jsonrpc_post(
            url,
            initialized_payload,
            timeout=timeout,
            extra_headers=notif_headers,
        )
    except (urllib.error.HTTPError, ValueError, json.JSONDecodeError) as e:
        # Some servers return non-2xx or odd shapes on notifications.
        # That's not fatal — the session is established; the
        # tools/call below is the real test. Emit a debug crumb so
        # operators can spot weird servers, but don't abort.
        emit_debug(f"notifications/initialized non-fatal failure: {e}")

    return session_id


def call_run_command(
    url: str,
    timeout: float,
    target: str,
    args: list[str],
    forwarded_env: dict[str, str],
    session_id: str,
) -> dict:
    """Invoke the host-bash MCP `run_command` tool.

    Builds the cli-mcp-server `run_command` invocation. Forwarded env
    vars are prepended via a `/usr/bin/env KEY=VAL ... <target> args`
    shape so cli-mcp-server still sees `env` as the binary it's exec'ing
    (which is in its default allow-list), and then `env` execs the real
    target with the env additions. The TARGET basename ALSO has to be
    in cli-mcp-server's ALLOWED_COMMANDS — that's an operator-side
    config (mcp-host-bash's CW_PROFILE / CLAUDE_HOOK_BRIDGE_BINS).

    `session_id` is the streamable-HTTP session id from
    `initialize_session`. Empty string means stateless mode (server
    didn't issue a session id), in which case we skip the header.
    """
    if forwarded_env:
        # Prepend `env KEY=VAL ...` to inject env vars on the host side
        # without needing cli-mcp-server to support a per-call env arg.
        prefix_args = [f"{k}={v}" for k, v in forwarded_env.items()] + [target] + list(args)
        rpc_command = "env"
        rpc_args = prefix_args
    else:
        rpc_command = target
        rpc_args = list(args)

    payload = {
        "jsonrpc": "2.0",
        "id": 2,
        "method": "tools/call",
        "params": {
            "name": "run_command",
            "arguments": {
                "command": rpc_command,
                "args": rpc_args,
            },
        },
    }
    extra_headers: dict[str, str] = {}
    if session_id:
        extra_headers[MCP_SESSION_ID_HEADER] = session_id
    extra_headers.update(bearer_header())
    body, _headers, _status = jsonrpc_post(
        url, payload, timeout=timeout,
        extra_headers=extra_headers if extra_headers else None,
    )
    if body is None:
        # tools/call should always return a body. Empty = server bug;
        # treat as unparseable so we fall back.
        raise ValueError("tools/call returned an empty body")
    return body


def parse_run_command_result(rpc_response: dict) -> tuple[int, str, str]:
    """Extract (exit_code, stdout, stderr) from cli-mcp-server's
    `run_command` response.

    cli-mcp-server returns the run result in `result.content[0].text`
    as a small text body that includes Stdout / Stderr / Exit-Code
    sections. The exact format is stable across releases (verified
    upstream cli-mcp-server v0.2.x); we parse it leniently and treat
    any unparseable shape as `(0, raw, "")` so we still propagate the
    payload back to Claude Code.
    """
    if "error" in rpc_response:
        err = rpc_response["error"]
        msg = err.get("message", str(err)) if isinstance(err, dict) else str(err)
        return (0, "", f"host-bash error: {msg}")
    result = rpc_response.get("result", {})
    if not isinstance(result, dict):
        return (0, str(result), "")
    if result.get("isError"):
        # cli-mcp-server signals allow-list rejection / disallowed flag
        # / shell-operator rejection here. Surface as stderr but exit 0
        # so the session doesn't fall over.
        content = result.get("content", [])
        text = content[0].get("text", str(content)) if content and isinstance(content[0], dict) else str(content)
        return (0, "", f"host-bash isError: {text}")
    content = result.get("content", [])
    if not content or not isinstance(content, list):
        return (0, "", "")
    first = content[0]
    if not isinstance(first, dict):
        return (0, str(first), "")
    text = first.get("text", "")
    if not isinstance(text, str):
        return (0, str(text), "")
    # cli-mcp-server's text body shape:
    #   Command executed successfully.
    #   Stdout: <stdout>
    #   Stderr: <stderr>
    #   Exit Code: <N>
    # Or on failure:
    #   Command failed: <reason>
    exit_code = 0
    stdout = ""
    stderr = ""
    lines = text.splitlines()
    in_stdout = False
    in_stderr = False
    stdout_buf: list[str] = []
    stderr_buf: list[str] = []
    for line in lines:
        if line.startswith("Stdout:"):
            in_stdout = True
            in_stderr = False
            tail = line[len("Stdout:"):].lstrip()
            if tail:
                stdout_buf.append(tail)
            continue
        if line.startswith("Stderr:"):
            in_stdout = False
            in_stderr = True
            tail = line[len("Stderr:"):].lstrip()
            if tail:
                stderr_buf.append(tail)
            continue
        if line.startswith("Exit Code:"):
            in_stdout = False
            in_stderr = False
            try:
                exit_code = int(line[len("Exit Code:"):].strip())
            except ValueError:
                pass
            continue
        if in_stdout:
            stdout_buf.append(line)
        elif in_stderr:
            stderr_buf.append(line)
    stdout = "\n".join(stdout_buf)
    stderr = "\n".join(stderr_buf)
    if not stdout and not stderr and not stdout_buf and not stderr_buf:
        # Couldn't parse — return the raw body as stdout for visibility.
        stdout = text
    return (exit_code, stdout, stderr)


# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Main
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------


def fall_back(reason: str) -> None:
    """Emit a one-line heads-up + exit 0 (silent-no-op contract)."""
    emit(f"falling back to no-op: {reason}")
    sys.exit(0)


def main(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    target, args = parse_argv(argv)

    if os.environ.get("CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE") != "1":
        # Bridge not enabled. Mirror the legacy silent-no-op behaviour
        # so this script is safe to install unconditionally — it only
        # wakes up when the operator opts in.
        sys.exit(0)

    url = bridge_url()
    timeout = bridge_timeout()
    forwarded = collect_forwarded_env()

    emit_debug(f"target={target} args={args} url={url} timeout={timeout}s forwarded_env={list(forwarded.keys())}")

    try:
        # MCP streamable-HTTP transport (mcp-proxy 0.11+ default) requires
        # a session handshake before tools/call — a bare tools/call POST
        # returns HTTP 400 "Bad Request: Missing session ID". We initialize
        # first, capture the server's mcp-session-id, then send tools/call
        # carrying that header.
        session_id = initialize_session(url, timeout)
        response = call_run_command(url, timeout, target, args, forwarded, session_id)
    except (urllib.error.URLError, TimeoutError, ConnectionError) as e:
        fall_back(f"host-bash unreachable: {e}")
    except (json.JSONDecodeError, ValueError) as e:
        fall_back(f"unparseable host-bash response: {e}")
    except Exception as e:  # pragma: no cover — last-resort safety
        fall_back(f"unexpected bridge error: {type(e).__name__}: {e}")

    exit_code, stdout, stderr = parse_run_command_result(response)
    if stdout:
        sys.stdout.write(stdout)
        if not stdout.endswith("\n"):
            sys.stdout.write("\n")
    if stderr:
        sys.stderr.write(stderr)
        if not stderr.endswith("\n"):
            sys.stderr.write("\n")
    sys.exit(exit_code)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main(sys.argv)
